Taiping Heavenly Kingdom Slavery nominally abolished along with opium, gambling, polygamy and foot binding.[2][3][4] New Granada Slavery abolished.[5] After years of laws that only purported a partial advancement towards abolition, President José Hilario López pushed Congress to pass total abolition on May 21. 
Former owners were compensated with government issued bonds.[6] Ecuador Slavery abolished in the country.[7] Lagos Reduction of Lagos: The British capture the city of Lagos and replace King Kosoko with Akitoye because of the former's refusal to ban the slave trade. 
1852 Hawaii 1852 Constitution officially declared slavery illegal.[8] United Kingdom Lagos Bilateral treaty banning the slave trade and human sacrifice. 
1853 Argentina Slavery abolished.[9] 1854 Peru Slavery abolished by Ramón Castilla.[10][11] Venezuela Slavery abolished.[11][5] Ottoman Empire Trade of Circassian children banned. 1855 Moldavia Slavery abolished. 
