It frees all remaining slaves, about 40,000, in the border slave states that did not secede.[18] Thirty out of thirty-six states vote to ratify it; New Jersey, Delaware, Kentucky, and Mississippi vote against. 
Mississippi does not ratify it until 2013.[19] Texas Juneteenth: U.S. General Gordon Granger proclaims the end of slavery in Galveston. 
Spain Spanish Abolitionist Society founded in Madrid by Julio Vizcarrondo, José Julián Acosta and Joaquín Sanromá.[20] 1866 Indian Territory Slavery abolished.[21] US government treaties with the "Five Civilized Tribes" in the Indian Territory (the Cherokee Nation, Choctaw Nation, Chickasaw Nation, Muscogee Nation, and Seminole Nation), which allied with the Confederacy, required all five tribes to abolish slavery for renewed US recognition of their governments. 
